                      <h3 class="text-center">ROOTS</h3>
                      <p>The roots of Valamo's monastery can be said to be over the millennia. In the mid-nineteenth
                        century as crusaders, middle-european monks brought distillation from Arabia to Europe. Until
                        1504, until the end of the Reformation, the monastery plant had the exclusive right to produce
                        distilled alcohol.</p>

                      <p>Along with just distilled alcohol, the roots of a whiskey made from grain are deep in the
                        tradition of monasteries. It is commonly believed that Irish monks have developed a modern
                        whiskey and subsequently ripened in oak barrels, from barrels from which the practice was passed
                        from whiskey manufacturing to industrialization up to bedrock. By the laws of the early 20th
                        century, whey distilled spirits could only be said to be whiskey after it had been aged for at
                        least three years in oak barrels.</p>

                      <%= image_tag 'text_bottle_black.png', class: 'spirit' %>
                      <!--<img class="spirit " src="http://www.valamodistillery.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/Heavenly-spirit-from-valamo-bw-680px.png" alt=""/>-->

                      <p>Since then, the abandonment of the monastery risk has been stopped by the monasteries and the
                        distillation of whiskey has shifted to wholemeal private distilleries. Today, almost every
                        continent is equipped with a bilge pan, but the main principles of distillation have remained
                        the same for centuries. Traditions are appreciated and they are to be kept up to date. At the
                        Valamo Monastery Distillery, this centuries-old tradition finally returns to its "home" when it
                        is currently the only manufacturer of monasteries in the world.</p>

                      <p>The heart of the whiskey is melted barley. Throughout the time the viscose was made from
                        barley, with the exception of small local specialties. Finnish barley is today a question of raw
                        material also in Scotland's distilleries in Scotland. Light long days in the Finnish summer,
                        nightless night, provide a barely favorable growth environment. Domestic barley is sugar and
                        starch and it gives the yeast an ideal workplace when making alcohol.</p>

                      <%= image_tag 'bar.png', class: 'viiva' %>
                      <!--<img class="viiva" src="http://www.valamodistillery.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/viiva-bw.png" alt=""/>-->

                    </div>
                    <div class="one_half last">

                      <h3 class="text-center">MATURATION</h3>
                      <p>The impact of the barrels on the end product of the product over the years has proved to be of
                        paramount importance. In general, whisking of whiskey in the distillery uses formerly Bourbon
                        whiskey barrels of the United States and dessert wine barrels. Bourbon shingles can be regarded
                        as the cornerstone of the whiskey industry.</p>

                      <p>Most of the world's malt bushes mature specifically in the bourbontynnyr. In dessert wines,
                        especially sherry's share is significant, but all of the maturing beverages are widely used in
                        maturing whiskey.</p>

                      <%= image_tag 'text_bottle_black.png', class: 'spirit' %>
                      <!--<img class="spirit " src="http://www.valamodistillery.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/Heavenly-spirit-from-valamo-bw-680px.png" alt=""/>-->

                      <p>The distillation of the malting pot of the Finnish Valamo Monastery started in summer 2015, but
                        before that, Valamo's monastery has been developed for more than four years. Our visk's roots
                        are in our vineyard, where the Valamo monastery's church wine is made. This grape-based liqueur
                        wine is used, among other things, in communion with numerous Finnish congregations.</p>

                      <p>The red wine is very sweet, fruity and ruby ​​red in color. This noble drink is aged for many
                        years in European oak barrels, which it absorbs over time, giving the barrel a beautiful red
                        tint from the inside.</p>

                      <p>We use this unique type of barrel in our whiskey production, ripening some of the distillate we
                        have prepared in church wine barrels. Especially the covenant of smoky whiskey and church wine
                        has turned out to be heavenly.</p>

                      <%= image_tag 'http://www.valamodistillery.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/viiva-bw.png', class: 'viiva' %>
                      <!--<img class="viiva" src="http://www.valamodistillery.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/viiva-bw.png" alt=""/>-->

